1
00:00:15,100 --> 00:00:18,103
Noppes

2
00:00:19,104 --> 00:00:21,106
The Iron Lady 2011 Cam XviD Feel-Free

3
00:01:37,012 --> 00:01:38,513
One forty-nine please.

4
00:01:41,242 --> 00:01:42,802
How much is the milk?

5
00:01:42,825 --> 00:01:44,500
Forty-nine pence.

6
00:01:50,387 --> 00:01:51,496
Thank you.

7
00:01:58,304 --> 00:01:59,439
Thank you.

8
00:02:35,418 --> 00:02:39,108
Too much. Much too much butter.
- I like butter.

9
00:02:46,889 --> 00:02:49,080
Milk’s gone up.

10
00:02:49,883 --> 00:02:52,886
49p a pint.

11
00:02:52,986 --> 00:02:55,913
Good grief! We’ll have to economise.

12
00:02:56,349 --> 00:03:01,077
I suppose we could always sell the car.
Or take in paying guests!

13
00:03:05,073 --> 00:03:07,429
Watch out. She’s on the prowl.

14
00:03:14,834 --> 00:03:16,427
Eat your egg.

15
00:03:20,342 --> 00:03:22,180
Goodness! There you are.

16
00:03:22,594 --> 00:03:25,070
Yes.
Here we are.

17
00:03:37,461 --> 00:03:39,159
I don’t understand how it happened,

18
00:03:39,194 --> 00:03:41,470
how could she possibly have got out?
It’s very very important -

19
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:45,612
Please just make it really clear.

20
00:03:45,613 --> 00:03:47,089
Who’s on after you?

21
00:03:47,090 --> 00:04:03,128
xxx?

22
00:04:14,360 --> 00:04:18,047
Beautiful day.
Oh, you’ve made a start.

23
00:04:18,082 --> 00:04:20,505
Carol’s coming soon,
I’ll get some bags.

24
00:04:22,451 --> 00:04:26,053
Anything you want to go to Mark,
I’ll bring up a suitcase for it.

25
00:04:34,318 --> 00:04:37,082
No no no no. The grey.

26
00:04:38,129 --> 00:04:39,206
You sure?

27
00:04:48,936 --> 00:04:51,611
Yes.
...Definitely the grey.

28
00:04:52,640 --> 00:04:53,942
Righty ho.

29
00:04:55,122 --> 00:04:56,711
Boss knows best.

30
00:05:05,754 --> 00:05:07,700
Don’t let her take my paper away.

31
00:05:08,224 --> 00:05:11,072
Oh, I haven’t had a chance to look
at that yet, dear.

32
00:05:11,379 --> 00:05:12,424
Sorry.

33
00:05:15,315 --> 00:05:16,358
Atta-girl.

34
00:05:18,378 --> 00:05:19,758
Damn.

35
00:05:21,525 --> 00:05:23,940
Blot it...Blot it..

36
00:05:24,341 --> 00:05:25,478
pardon.

37
00:05:35,071 --> 00:05:36,781
Now look what you’ve done.

38
00:05:38,442 --> 00:05:41,302
Are they to keep the loonies
out or you in?

39
00:05:44,889 --> 00:05:46,050
I’ll be off then.

40
00:05:46,102 --> 00:05:50,831
Wear your scarf.
There’s a chill out there.

41
00:05:54,765 --> 00:05:56,564
Good morning Lady Thatcher.

42
00:05:56,796 --> 00:05:59,276
Are you alright?
How are you feeling?

43
00:06:00,076 --> 00:06:02,934
I’m fine, thank you Susie.

44
00:06:02,969 --> 00:06:05,671
I’ve just been reading about the bombings.

45
00:06:05,699 --> 00:06:07,588
Yes. Frightful.

46
00:06:15,628 --> 00:06:16,629
Sorry.

47
00:06:18,751 --> 00:06:20,681
These are the books for you to sign.

48
00:06:20,682 --> 00:06:26,045
I brought as many as I could find.
Shall we go through your appointments?

49
00:06:27,055 --> 00:06:29,835
We said we’d go through them today.

50
00:06:30,112 --> 00:06:33,717
Yes, of course, dear. Today.

51
00:06:33,730 --> 00:06:36,956
The invitation has come from Downing Street
for the unveiling of your portrait.

52
00:06:37,085 --> 00:06:40,740
I’ll put it on the mantelpiece, and there’s
an invitation from Lord Armstrong for

53
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:43,325
lunch on the first Friday of next month.

54
00:06:43,330 --> 00:06:47,638
I said no because you’ve got a concert
that afternoon but if you’d like to...

55
00:06:47,873 --> 00:06:50,303
It looks like a very interesting programme.

56
00:06:50,338 --> 00:06:51,987
What are they playing?

57
00:06:53,328 --> 00:06:59,252
I think they said Rogers and Hammerstein.

58
00:07:32,688 --> 00:07:34,588
Silly man.

59
00:07:35,347 --> 00:07:38,344
He hasn’t got his scarf on.

60
00:08:19,521 --> 00:08:21,020
Did someone cover the butter?

61
00:08:23,017 --> 00:08:23,842
I’ll go.

62
00:08:23,971 --> 00:08:25,420
Leave it. Margaret-

63
00:08:33,428 --> 00:08:34,708
Good girl.

64
00:08:36,922 --> 00:08:41,990
Tomorrow, no matter what they do,
it’ll be business as usual.

65
00:08:46,117 --> 00:08:47,889
Two of the small beef, Mr. Roberts.

66
00:08:48,913 --> 00:08:53,542
What is the life blood of any community?
It’s business...

67
00:08:53,578 --> 00:08:56,451
Not just big business but small
businesses, like mine.

68
00:08:56,532 --> 00:08:57,845
Margaret! CUPS!

69
00:08:57,880 --> 00:09:01,972
We on this island are strong.
We’re self-reliant.

70
00:09:01,973 --> 00:09:04,655
Sometimes
we’re plain bloody minded.

71
00:09:04,690 --> 00:09:07,344
But we also believe in helping
each other.

72
00:09:07,379 --> 00:09:09,243
And I don’t mean by
state hand-outs...

73
00:09:09,278 --> 00:09:11,176
Margaret, do you want to come to
the pictures?

74
00:09:11,211 --> 00:09:13,306
She can’t come, she’s got to study.

75
00:09:13,341 --> 00:09:14,836
Miss Hoity Toity!

76
00:09:15,753 --> 00:09:19,323
Never run with the crowd, Margaret.
Go your own way.

77
00:09:20,880 --> 00:09:27,063
xxxOpen it then.

78
00:09:30,825 --> 00:09:33,098
I’ve got a place at Oxford.

79
00:09:38,842 --> 00:09:40,635
Don’t let me down Margaret.

80
00:09:41,566 --> 00:09:42,646
Mother?

81
00:09:46,281 --> 00:09:48,366
My hands are still damp.

82
00:10:11,918 --> 00:10:13,920
Margaret!CUPS!

83
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:22,365
They’re talking about you again.

84
00:10:22,689 --> 00:10:25,436
What time is it?

85
00:10:27,212 --> 00:10:31,230
Sun’s not quite over the yard arm.
Time for tea.

86
00:10:37,739 --> 00:10:39,598
What have you got on your head?

87
00:10:39,628 --> 00:10:44,575
Found it in the cupboard and thought bugger
it, it’s Friday, why not fancy dress?

88
00:10:44,873 --> 00:10:46,495
You look ridiculous.

89
00:10:46,738 --> 00:10:48,650
Bosslady no like?

90
00:10:48,794 --> 00:10:51,392
No, Denis, Bosslady no like.

91
00:11:16,655 --> 00:11:19,405
Can I suggest you remove the
sticker from the back of your car.

92
00:11:19,440 --> 00:11:20,703
xxx

93
00:11:20,938 --> 00:11:23,704
Well then take the sticker off!
I call that false advertising!

94
00:11:23,739 --> 00:11:25,750
xxx
- I would say keep the change...

95
00:11:25,785 --> 00:11:26,955
but there isn’t any change.

96
00:11:27,104 --> 00:11:30,989
Hello June, any news? I’ve brought
every bag I could find.

97
00:11:31,585 --> 00:11:37,720
xxx

98
00:11:37,755 --> 00:11:38,565
Hello Ma.

99
00:11:39,167 --> 00:11:41,798
Bloody taxi driver.
Wouldn’t take my card.

100
00:11:41,833 --> 00:11:46,609
I said don’t have a sticker saying you
take Visa and then insist on cash.

101
00:11:47,552 --> 00:11:50,829
Can you believe it? I was rummaging around
the bottom of my bag. He didn’t get a tip.

102
00:11:54,695 --> 00:11:59,711
I didn’t know that you were
dropping by today, dear.

103
00:12:00,670 --> 00:12:03,619
Yes, you said yesterday...
You wanted to make a start on Dad’s things.

104
00:12:04,486 --> 00:12:06,671
The cupboards?
Then I can help you dress.

105
00:12:06,713 --> 00:12:08,993
You’ve got Michael and-

106
00:12:09,347 --> 00:12:11,029
Jaqueline...
Coming for dinner tonight.

107
00:12:11,165 --> 00:12:12,486
Of course.

108
00:12:14,883 --> 00:12:16,526
We’re having halibut.

109
00:12:23,157 --> 00:12:27,081
Oh God. Isn’t it terrible?
They think it’s Al Quaida -

110
00:12:27,258 --> 00:12:30,206
xxx

111
00:12:36,324 --> 00:12:40,574
It’ll be fine. Come on, get your head down,
it’s ten to three, for God’s sake.

112
00:12:40,609 --> 00:12:43,371
At ten to three this morning
an explosion...

113
00:12:43,406 --> 00:12:46,282
extensively damaged
the Grand Hotel in Brighton

114
00:12:46,316 --> 00:12:48,920
scene of the Conservative
Party conference.

115
00:12:48,955 --> 00:12:52,121
Where the Prime Minister and a
number of her cabinet were staying.

116
00:12:52,242 --> 00:12:53,814
They escaped unhurt -

117
00:12:53,920 --> 00:12:58,358
Five people have died, many others
are injured, some critically.

118
00:12:58,606 --> 00:13:01,248
The IRA have claimed responsibility.

119
00:13:03,440 --> 00:13:08,311
We must release a statement,
offering our condolences.

120
00:13:08,946 --> 00:13:10,812
I’m sure they’ve already-

121
00:13:10,870 --> 00:13:15,154
We must never, ever, ever give in
to terrorists.

122
00:13:19,168 --> 00:13:21,249
Good moring dear.

123
00:13:23,517 --> 00:13:26,125
Now ma, are we going long or just
below the knee tonight?

124
00:13:26,270 --> 00:13:28,641
Oh, below the knee I should think.

125
00:13:31,572 --> 00:13:37,796
No! Don’t move those. I haven’t
finished sorting them.

126
00:13:46,925 --> 00:13:48,534
I hear you went out today...

127
00:13:50,954 --> 00:13:53,590
You mustn’t go out on your own Mummy.
We’ve talked about that.

128
00:13:54,667 --> 00:13:56,147
There was no milk.

129
00:13:56,218 --> 00:13:59,267
Call Robert he’ll get it for you
if June’s not up-

130
00:13:59,367 --> 00:14:01,558
I am not for the knackers yet.

131
00:14:01,597 --> 00:14:03,194
Now take it easy, Margaret.

132
00:14:03,203 --> 00:14:04,735
No one is saying that.

133
00:14:06,485 --> 00:14:11,629
If I can’t go out to buy a pint of milk
then what is the world coming to.

134
00:14:11,664 --> 00:14:12,630
Really Carol...

135
00:14:14,034 --> 00:14:16,515
please don’t fuss about it.

136
00:14:17,266 --> 00:14:21,315
You’ve always been like this,
fuss fuss fuss.

137
00:14:22,006 --> 00:14:25,253
You must find something better
to do with your time.

138
00:14:26,219 --> 00:14:29,062
It’s most unattractive in a woman.

139
00:14:29,990 --> 00:14:31,859
When I was your age...

140
00:14:31,894 --> 00:14:36,272
the last thing I wanted to do
was fuss around my mother.

141
00:14:38,463 --> 00:14:40,476
Four down, 9 letters.

142
00:14:40,499 --> 00:14:43,380
Something b something t
something n...

143
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:47,153
something something somthing...
Refusal to change course-

144
00:14:48,078 --> 00:14:49,985
Obstinate.

145
00:14:49,993 --> 00:14:52,804
What?

146
00:14:54,992 --> 00:14:56,377
Pearls.
I’ll wear the pearls.

147
00:15:10,186 --> 00:15:13,849
There they are.
My little twins.

148
00:15:17,061 --> 00:15:18,359
Thank you, dear.

149
00:15:20,059 --> 00:15:24,561
It’s nearly all familiar faces, William,
Michael and his lovely wife-

150
00:15:24,596 --> 00:15:25,554
Jacqueline.

151
00:15:25,589 --> 00:15:31,421
And then there’s Peter, James R
and James T and that very nice man-

152
00:15:31,456 --> 00:15:33,878
Yes-
we met last year.

153
00:15:33,913 --> 00:15:34,896
Yes I remember-

154
00:15:34,996 --> 00:15:37,762
I think he’s bringing his new lady
friend just to mix it up a bit.

155
00:15:37,798 --> 00:15:41,256
We’re rather short on women - but
I’m sure we’ll manage-

156
00:15:41,291 --> 00:15:43,856
I’ve always preferred the company
of men-

157
00:15:47,003 --> 00:15:48,004
Ma?

158
00:15:57,598 --> 00:15:58,600
Ah, Miss Roberts.

159
00:15:58,635 --> 00:16:02,498
Hoping to be chosen as
our candidate for parliament.

160
00:16:02,511 --> 00:16:06,851
Well I don’t like coalitions,
never have...

161
00:16:16,903 --> 00:16:19,427
Start on the outside
and work your way in.

162
00:16:19,462 --> 00:16:23,436
Attlee has his sights set on
the steel industry, you mark my words.

163
00:16:23,485 --> 00:16:25,690
They’ll be nationalizing the
bloody air next.

164
00:16:25,725 --> 00:16:28,541
Yes, hold your breath, sir, that’s
government property!

165
00:16:29,561 --> 00:16:33,110
So was your father a political
man, too, Miss Roberts?

166
00:16:33,177 --> 00:16:38,088
Oh, yes, to his core. And Mayor of
Grantham.

167
00:16:38,334 --> 00:16:41,779
And a grocer as well!

168
00:16:41,823 --> 00:16:42,720
Yes.

169
00:16:42,755 --> 00:16:49,210
And did you help, in the... shop?
- Oh, yes. It was a family business.

170
00:16:49,324 --> 00:16:52,243
A very good starting point for the
political life, I’m sure.

171
00:16:52,343 --> 00:16:54,655
That and a degree from Oxford.

172
00:17:01,569 --> 00:17:03,288
Whisky.

173
00:17:11,082 --> 00:17:15,800
What I do think is that a man should be
encouraged to stand on his own two feet.

174
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:21,051
Yes we help people of course we help people.
But for those that can do...

175
00:17:21,086 --> 00:17:24,393
they must just get up and do.

176
00:17:24,429 --> 00:17:27,577
And if something’s wrong,
they shouldn’t just whine about it...

177
00:17:27,612 --> 00:17:32,080
they should get in there and DO
something about it, change things.

178
00:17:32,115 --> 00:17:35,319
With all due respect, Miss Roberts,
what may have served in Grantham-

179
00:17:35,354 --> 00:17:38,191
Can serve very well for the people
of Dartford too.

180
00:17:38,226 --> 00:17:38,924
Really?

181
00:17:38,959 --> 00:17:43,005
I know much more than those who
have never lived on a limited income.

182
00:17:43,040 --> 00:17:47,220
Just like the man or woman on the street,
when I am short one week...

183
00:17:47,255 --> 00:17:49,827
I have to make economies the next.

184
00:17:49,905 --> 00:17:53,088
Nothing like a slice of fiscal
responsibility.

185
00:17:53,124 --> 00:17:58,907
A man might call it fiscal responsibility,
a woman might call it good housekeeping.

186
00:17:58,975 --> 00:18:00,335
I’m not sure...

187
00:18:00,370 --> 00:18:04,680
a home economics lesson
is quite what...

188
00:18:04,715 --> 00:18:06,969
the Dartford constituents need.

189
00:18:07,003 --> 00:18:10,077
They see industry being nationalized...

190
00:18:10,112 --> 00:18:13,737
the unions on the up,
the pound on the slide...

191
00:18:14,082 --> 00:18:18,329
whoever can sort that lot out,
he’s my man.

192
00:18:18,364 --> 00:18:19,388
Or woman?

193
00:18:24,333 --> 00:18:26,603
Ladies shall we?

194
00:18:28,027 --> 00:18:30,908
Miss Roberts, do join the ladies.

195
00:18:44,918 --> 00:18:47,923
Well. That’s told us!

196
00:18:52,168 --> 00:18:56,134
So, Margaret, how would you have
dealt with this if you’d been Prime Minister?

197
00:18:57,221 --> 00:18:58,643
Where?

198
00:18:59,785 --> 00:19:03,021
The bombings, mummy. Today?

199
00:19:04,335 --> 00:19:06,180
We were just talking about them?

200
00:19:09,132 --> 00:19:13,817
No, uhm, yes -
we have always lived alongside evil.

201
00:19:13,852 --> 00:19:18,122
But it has never been so patient,

202
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:24,856
so avid for carnage, so eager to
carry innocents with it into oblivion.

203
00:19:24,891 --> 00:19:26,647
xxxSo, would you -

204
00:19:26,682 --> 00:19:31,982
Western civilization must root out
this evil, wherever it hides,

205
00:19:32,017 --> 00:19:37,386
or she risks defeat at the hands
of global terror in a nuclear age.

206
00:19:37,421 --> 00:19:38,543
Unimaginable!

207
00:19:38,578 --> 00:19:40,622
The Prime Minister gave a very
good statement I thought.

208
00:19:40,657 --> 00:19:43,623
Yes. Clever man. Quite a smoothie.

209
00:19:45,703 --> 00:19:50,364
xxxYou don’t mind if I sit down...

210
00:19:50,399 --> 00:19:56,348
I heard you speak at conference
in Brighton in 1984

211
00:19:56,383 --> 00:19:58,790
just after the IRA bombed
the Grand Hotel.

212
00:19:59,861 --> 00:20:02,201
You were remarkable.

213
00:20:03,455 --> 00:20:07,861
I hope you appreciate what an inspiration
you have been for women like myself.

214
00:20:09,077 --> 00:20:13,028
It used to be about trying
to do something.

215
00:20:14,584 --> 00:20:18,359
Now its about trying to be someone.

216
00:20:24,263 --> 00:20:26,752
Well anyway, I...thank you.

217
00:20:26,853 --> 00:20:29,272
Good night, Lady Th...
- Good night to you.

218
00:20:48,878 --> 00:20:50,803
OK...hold on to me...

219
00:20:57,152 --> 00:21:00,340
Can you do the clasp, I can’t quite -

220
00:21:00,375 --> 00:21:02,517
Thank you.

221
00:21:05,871 --> 00:21:07,483
You’ve got an eyelash.

222
00:21:09,147 --> 00:21:10,496
Make a wish.

223
00:21:22,562 --> 00:21:24,700
I spoke to Doctor Michael today-

224
00:21:26,279 --> 00:21:28,967
He is very good and very expensive-

225
00:21:30,341 --> 00:21:33,274
...I know you’re not due to see
him for another month

226
00:21:34,222 --> 00:21:37,434
but I’ve spoken to him and he can fit
you in tomorrow.

227
00:21:39,368 --> 00:21:40,778
Just for a check up.

228
00:21:42,921 --> 00:21:44,505
Ma please-

229
00:21:45,627 --> 00:21:48,200
What does Mark think about it?

230
00:21:48,235 --> 00:21:50,367
Mark?

231
00:21:53,718 --> 00:21:57,293
Yes. Tell him to come up. I want
to talk to him about it.

232
00:21:59,021 --> 00:22:01,899
Mark’s with Sarah and the
children.

233
00:22:06,689 --> 00:22:09,948
Well tell him to come up
and see me after he’s...

234
00:22:09,983 --> 00:22:12,478
kissed them good night,
would you Carol darling?

235
00:22:30,938 --> 00:22:32,653
He’s not here Mummy.

236
00:22:35,463 --> 00:22:37,405
Mark lives in South Africa...

237
00:22:41,090 --> 00:22:43,390
you are not Prime Minister anymore...

238
00:22:47,698 --> 00:22:51,893
and Dad is...
Dad is dead-

239
00:23:00,612 --> 00:23:03,208
You look exhausted, dear.

240
00:23:06,925 --> 00:23:11,303
You really must try to get some sleep.

241
00:23:15,598 --> 00:23:19,362
Taxis'll be few and far
between at this hour...

242
00:23:24,867 --> 00:23:27,559
Righty-ho. Night night Ma.
Sleep well.

243
00:23:27,719 --> 00:23:29,694
Good night, dear.

244
00:24:16,827 --> 00:24:21,171
Twenty-four-year-old Miss Margaret Roberts
lost her bid to win a seat in Parliament today,

245
00:24:21,206 --> 00:24:24,983
but she has put new life into the Dartford
Conservative Association.

246
00:24:25,018 --> 00:24:27,793
Winning candidate Mr Dodds
had better watch out,

247
00:24:27,828 --> 00:24:30,128
this bright young woman
is on his tail.

248
00:24:40,663 --> 00:24:41,998
Eat!

249
00:24:43,382 --> 00:24:44,954
Disaster.

250
00:24:44,989 --> 00:24:46,623
Hang on...Hang on...

251
00:24:48,041 --> 00:24:49,236
xxx

