00:30:45,711 --> 00:31:00,547
xxx

303
00:32:23,338 --> 00:32:24,260
Mrs Thatcher!

304
00:32:26,601 --> 00:32:32,191
Mrs Thatcher! Airey Neave.
Welcome to the madhouse. Follow me.

305
00:32:40,311 --> 00:32:43,769
Welcome... xxx

306
00:32:58,035 --> 00:32:59,971
Order

307
00:33:00,431 --> 00:33:03,680
The Right Honourable Lady the
Secretary of State for Education.

308
00:33:05,031 --> 00:33:11,370
The right honourable gentleman knows
that we have no choice but to shut down the schools!

309
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:14,494
Because...

310
00:33:16,931 --> 00:33:24,070
his union paymasters have called a
strike deliberately to cripple our economy.

311
00:33:26,939 --> 00:33:32,842
Teachers cannot teach when there is no
heating, no lighting in their classrooms.

312
00:33:32,877 --> 00:33:36,988
And I ask the honourable gentleman,
whose fault is that?

313
00:33:41,760 --> 00:33:46,976
Me thinks the Right Honourable
lady doth screech to much.

314
00:33:50,300 --> 00:33:56,126
If she wants us to take her seriously
she must learn to calm down!

315
00:33:59,534 --> 00:34:03,455
If the right honorable gentleman could
perhaps attend more closely to...

316
00:34:03,490 --> 00:34:07,642
What I am saying,
rather than HOW I am saying it,

317
00:34:08,116 --> 00:34:13,105
he may receive a valuable
education in spite of himself!

318
00:34:14,435 --> 00:34:19,555
Why has this Conservative
government failed?

319
00:34:22,051 --> 00:34:26,109
Why has it forced so many
in the public sector into

320
00:34:26,145 --> 00:34:30,377
taking strike action
to save their own jobs?

321
00:34:34,904 --> 00:34:35,939
Minister...

322
00:34:36,609 --> 00:34:42,249
the breakdown of essential public
services in transport, electricity...

323
00:34:42,284 --> 00:34:46,262
sanitation is not the fault
of the trades unions...

324
00:34:46,297 --> 00:34:50,716
but of this Conservative government

325
00:34:50,751 --> 00:34:53,722
in which you so shamefully serve!

326
00:35:07,370 --> 00:35:11,046
So these power cuts will continue
unless we can reach a compromise.

327
00:35:11,546 --> 00:35:15,797
The miners are asking for
a 35% increase in wages.

328
00:35:15,832 --> 00:35:18,193
Obviously we can’t go
anywhere near that.

329
00:35:18,228 --> 00:35:21,660
The unions are not our enemies
and never have been.

330
00:35:21,696 --> 00:35:25,727
We want- and have always wanted
the broadest consensus…

331
00:35:27,254 --> 00:35:29,521
I’m sure we are all in agreement
that we must do nothing...

332
00:35:29,556 --> 00:35:32,337
for the moment that will further
inflame the current situation.

333
00:35:32,372 --> 00:35:33,782
Hear hear, Prime Minister.

334
00:35:33,817 --> 00:35:36,531
- the fact of the matter is,
it’s absolutely crucial...

335
00:35:36,566 --> 00:35:39,908
that we are seen by the public
to be acting as conciliators...

336
00:35:39,943 --> 00:35:42,707
and not aggressors.
- Yes.

337
00:35:46,600 --> 00:35:47,912
Yes, Education Secretary.

338
00:35:47,947 --> 00:35:49,425
Yes, Prime Minister.

339
00:35:49,460 --> 00:35:53,944
With the Miners’ leader calling
today for the army to mutiny...

340
00:35:53,980 --> 00:35:57,971
in support of the strikes, this seems
the wrong time for conciliation.

341
00:36:01,133 --> 00:36:04,540
Be patient. They’ll come back
on in a minute.

342
00:36:04,575 --> 00:36:08,573
xxx

343
00:36:09,318 --> 00:36:11,346
Thank you, Margaret.

344
00:36:13,357 --> 00:36:16,155
Your thoughts are duly noted.

345
00:36:22,976 --> 00:36:25,394
We on this island are strong.

346
00:36:25,895 --> 00:36:30,923
We’re self-reliant. Napoleon
called us a nation of shopkeepers.

347
00:36:31,107 --> 00:36:34,148
He meant it as an insult
but to me it’s a compliment.

348
00:36:34,183 --> 00:36:37,793
That’s why he couldn’t beat us,
and that’s why Hitler can’t beat us.

349
00:36:40,143 --> 00:36:45,258
We Conservatives believe in giving people
the freedom and opportunity to...

350
00:36:45,293 --> 00:36:48,521
fulfil their own potential,
especially the young.

351
00:36:48,556 --> 00:36:50,443
There’s no good in pretending
we’re all equal...

352
00:36:50,478 --> 00:36:52,935
we’re not all the same, never
have been, never will be.

353
00:36:53,843 --> 00:36:59,525
We should encourage our children to
aspire to achieve more than we have...

354
00:36:59,560 --> 00:37:03,495
for our children today will
be the leaders of tomorrow.

355
00:37:05,781 --> 00:37:08,994
It’s 1974 and you’d think
it was WWII.

356
00:37:09,029 --> 00:37:11,343
Blackouts, no petrol.
It’s a mess.

357
00:37:11,378 --> 00:37:16,119
Heath should resign now and make way
for someone who’s not afraid to tackle the unions.

358
00:37:16,154 --> 00:37:18,254
I swear, it’s all gone completely
out of my head.

359
00:37:18,289 --> 00:37:22,270
My driving instructor thinks I should pass
but I feel as if I’ve hardly had any lessons.

360
00:37:22,305 --> 00:37:25,679
Ridiculous isn’t it?
Maybe third time lucky.

361
00:37:25,759 --> 00:37:26,575
Right.

362
00:37:26,610 --> 00:37:31,959
The only thing you should remember is
that everyone else is either reckless or inept.

363
00:37:32,035 --> 00:37:33,734
And often both.

364
00:37:33,819 --> 00:37:36,934
One must be brave if one is to
take the wheel-

365
00:37:37,035 --> 00:37:38,322
Right-o.

366
00:37:39,114 --> 00:37:41,755
Move over... Move to your right a
little bit...

367
00:37:41,790 --> 00:37:44,167
But if I move to the right aren’t
I on the wrong side of the road?

368
00:37:44,864 --> 00:37:47,379
Well he’s in the way!
- To the right. Move to the right!

369
00:37:49,777 --> 00:37:52,576
So sorry! Terribly sorry!

370
00:37:58,731 --> 00:38:00,462
Hey, look at me, driving!

371
00:38:00,497 --> 00:38:04,285
Thanks Ma, that was terrific! I
really feel I’ve got a handle on it now.

372
00:38:04,320 --> 00:38:05,630
You should have seen us, Pa.

373
00:38:05,665 --> 00:38:09,580
Have you been trying to make
breakfast? For Goodness sake, Denis!

374
00:38:09,615 --> 00:38:11,446
I can boil a bloody egg.

375
00:38:11,481 --> 00:38:12,493
Mummy took me for a test drive -

376
00:38:12,528 --> 00:38:14,787
We went absolutely everywhere.
All over the place -

377
00:38:14,822 --> 00:38:18,257
I’ve decided. I’m going to run.

378
00:38:18,292 --> 00:38:19,484
What for?

379
00:38:21,471 --> 00:38:24,528
I’m going to run for Leader of the Party.

380
00:38:30,053 --> 00:38:31,834
Silly me!
- Good luck!

381
00:38:31,869 --> 00:38:36,027
All the time I thought I was having a driving lesson,
it was all about my mother, just for a change!

382
00:38:36,062 --> 00:38:37,576
What’s she on about?

383
00:38:37,611 --> 00:38:40,539
It’s her driving test this morning!
- Oh, right. Of course.

384
00:38:41,015 --> 00:38:44,216
Are you saying you want to be
Prime Minister?

385
00:38:44,918 --> 00:38:49,950
What I’m saying is that someone
must force the point,

386
00:38:49,985 --> 00:38:54,193
say the unsayable. None of these
men have the guts.

387
00:38:55,588 --> 00:38:58,696
The Prime Minister has been very
loyal to you, MT.

388
00:38:58,731 --> 00:39:01,396
But he’s weak, and he’s
weakened the party.

389
00:39:02,690 --> 00:39:06,681
One must know when to go.
You’re shaking.

390
00:39:06,845 --> 00:39:08,290
Let... xxx
- I can do it!

391
00:39:08,774 --> 00:39:10,971
Goodness me!

392
00:39:13,969 --> 00:39:16,143
What is the matter
with everyone this morning?

393
00:39:16,178 --> 00:39:17,359
I’ve told you what the matter is.

394
00:39:17,395 --> 00:39:21,046
The business is a bit rocky at the moment
and the Doctor thinks I need a rest.

395
00:39:21,081 --> 00:39:22,571
And do you need a rest?

396
00:39:25,847 --> 00:39:26,972
We both know...

397
00:39:27,838 --> 00:39:31,923
that it’s highly unlikely that I
would ever be elected leader,

398
00:39:31,957 --> 00:39:33,971
But I will run. I will run.

399
00:39:34,006 --> 00:39:36,045
Just to nip at their heels and make...

400
00:39:36,080 --> 00:39:40,733
them reaffirm the principles on which
the Conservative Party must stand.

401
00:39:44,314 --> 00:39:46,021
There’s so much to do.

402
00:39:47,188 --> 00:39:49,868
You’re insufferable, Margaret,
do you know that?

403
00:39:52,327 --> 00:39:57,098
Denis, you married someone who is committed
to public service, you knew that.

404
00:39:58,392 --> 00:40:01,708
And it is my duty...
- Don’t call it duty.

405
00:40:01,743 --> 00:40:04,714
It’s ambition which has got
you this far. Ambition.

406
00:40:04,749 --> 00:40:09,139
And the rest of us, me, the children,
we can all go to hell!

407
00:40:10,872 --> 00:40:13,248
Don’t worry about me,
I’ll be fine!

408
00:40:13,805 --> 00:40:15,647
Where did you go?

409
00:40:15,682 --> 00:40:17,682
South Africa.
- Yes.Yes.

410
00:40:18,300 --> 00:40:21,324
How many days passed before
you realized I was gone?

411
00:40:22,280 --> 00:40:25,096
Probably had to ask the cleaning
woman where I was.

412
00:40:25,414 --> 00:40:28,073
When did I lose track of everyone?

413
00:40:29,129 --> 00:40:32,073
Too busy climbing the greasy pole MT.

414
00:40:32,108 --> 00:40:35,880
Mrs Thatcher I understand you
recently visited the United States of America.

415
00:40:36,878 --> 00:40:41,556
What was it you took away from that visit
which may be of value here in Great Britain?

416
00:40:41,591 --> 00:40:43,531
Oh that’s rather easy
to answer, actually.

417
00:40:43,566 --> 00:40:47,299
They are unafraid of success.

418
00:40:48,359 --> 00:40:53,677
We in Great Britain and in Europe
are formed mainly by our history.

419
00:40:53,712 --> 00:40:57,673
They on the other hand are
formed by their philosophy.

420
00:40:57,708 --> 00:41:01,347
Not by what has been,
but by what can be.

421
00:41:01,383 --> 00:41:06,793
Oh, we have a great deal that we
can learn from them, yes. Oh yes!

422
00:41:17,860 --> 00:41:21,060
For a start, that hat
has got to go.

423
00:41:21,096 --> 00:41:22,345
And the pearls.

424
00:41:22,380 --> 00:41:26,348
In fact I think all hats may have to go.

425
00:41:27,354 --> 00:41:29,413
You look and sound like...

426
00:41:29,448 --> 00:41:33,850
a privileged Conservative wife
and we’ve already got her vote.

427
00:41:33,885 --> 00:41:35,797
You’ve got lovely hair...

428
00:41:35,832 --> 00:41:39,901
but we need to do something with it
to make it more, Important.

429
00:41:39,936 --> 00:41:41,592
Yes. Give it more impact.

430
00:41:41,857 --> 00:41:47,250
But the main thing is your voice.
Its too high. It has no authority.

431
00:41:47,313 --> 00:41:50,971
Me thinks the Lady doth screech too much

432
00:41:51,006 --> 00:41:54,884
People don’t want to be harangued
by a woman or hectored.

433
00:41:54,919 --> 00:41:57,657
Persuaded yes.
That ‘oh yes’...

434
00:41:57,692 --> 00:41:59,442
at the end of the interview,

435
00:41:59,477 --> 00:42:02,087
that’s authoritative,
that’s the voice of a leader.

436
00:42:03,388 --> 00:42:07,814
It’s all very well to talk about
changing my voice, Mr Reece,

437
00:42:07,849 --> 00:42:12,457
but for some of my colleagues to
imagine me as their leader...

438
00:42:13,315 --> 00:42:14,850
would be like imagining,

439
00:42:14,885 --> 00:42:18,666
I don’t know, being led into
battle by their chambermaid.

440
00:42:18,701 --> 00:42:21,487
It’s my background, and my sex.

441
00:42:22,745 --> 00:42:25,551
No matter how I’ve tried,
and I have tried...

442
00:42:26,192 --> 00:42:30,088
to fit in, xxx
I will never be truly one of them.

443
00:42:30,153 --> 00:42:33,342
If I may say so - I think that’s
your trump card.

444
00:42:33,377 --> 00:42:36,978
You’re flying in the face of everything
the Tories have been thus far.

445
00:42:37,013 --> 00:42:39,799
It’s really very exciting.

446
00:42:40,306 --> 00:42:44,228
One simply has to maximise
your appeal...

447
00:42:44,263 --> 00:42:46,812
bring out all your qualities...

448
00:42:46,847 --> 00:42:51,029
and make you look, and sound,
like the leader that you could be.

449
00:42:51,064 --> 00:42:53,173
You’ve got it in you to go the
whole distance.

450
00:42:53,208 --> 00:42:54,012
Absolutely.

451
00:42:56,654 --> 00:42:58,291
Prime Minister?!

452
00:42:59,641 --> 00:43:05,383
Oh no. Oh no no no. In Britain?

453
00:43:05,899 --> 00:43:11,647
There will be no female Prime Minister
here, not in my lifetime.

454
00:43:11,682 --> 00:43:12,938
No.

455
00:43:12,973 --> 00:43:18,245
And I told Airey, I don’t expect
to win the leadership, but I...

456
00:43:18,279 --> 00:43:22,211
am going to run.
Just to shake up the party.

457
00:43:22,246 --> 00:43:24,055
Respectfully, Margaret,

458
00:43:24,433 --> 00:43:28,050
I disagree.
If you want to change this party,

459
00:43:28,085 --> 00:43:31,236
lead it. If you want to change
the country, lead it.

460
00:43:31,271 --> 00:43:35,822
What we’re talking about here
today is surface. What’s crucial...

461
00:43:35,857 --> 00:43:39,339
is that you hold your course, and
stay true to who you are.

462
00:43:39,374 --> 00:43:41,751
Never be anything other
than yourself.

463
00:43:41,752 --> 00:43:43,638
Leave us to do the rest.

464
00:43:51,226 --> 00:43:53,948
Gentlemen, I am in your hands.

465
00:43:54,569 --> 00:43:58,296
I may be persuaded to
surrender the hat.

466
00:43:58,331 --> 00:44:03,195
But the pearls were a gift from my
husband on the birth of our twins...

467
00:44:03,230 --> 00:44:09,203
and they are absolutely
non-negotiable.

468
00:44:15,662 --> 00:44:18,024
Good, I think we can loose
the handbag, Mrs Thatcher.

469
00:44:19,272 --> 00:44:21,600
Hands down the sides...

470
00:44:21,601 --> 00:44:23,491
And...bring it down.

471
00:44:26,964 --> 00:44:30,652
Because this isn’t really about
the voice, it’s about belief...

472
00:44:30,687 --> 00:44:33,046
A nice deep breath.

473
00:44:33,047 --> 00:44:34,917
xxx hands

474
00:44:39,656 --> 00:44:41,473
If you’re calling Mr Thatcher,
how would you do that?

475
00:44:41,508 --> 00:44:42,315
Denis.

476
00:44:42,350 --> 00:44:45,026
Yes, I want more authority,
I want conviction, I want...

477
00:44:45,061 --> 00:44:48,451
That’s right, one more time,
deep breath -

478
00:44:48,486 --> 00:44:49,428
Denis.

479
00:44:49,463 --> 00:44:51,823
Yes MT!

480
00:44:54,784 --> 00:44:57,727
You are the backbone
of our nation!

481
00:44:57,762 --> 00:45:00,779
Small firms like Loveday’s Ice Cream.

482
00:45:00,814 --> 00:45:02,742
How are you?
So nice to meet you ladies.

483
00:45:02,777 --> 00:45:06,080
I’ll just have a small one,
because I’m watching my figure.

484
00:45:07,128 --> 00:45:08,854
That’s for you young man!

485
00:45:08,889 --> 00:45:13,922
I passionately believe it’s the growth
of small businesses into larger ones...

486
00:45:13,957 --> 00:45:16,861
that is critical for
Britain’s future.

487
00:45:16,896 --> 00:45:20,242
It has to be something icy on
a stick for Denis.

488
00:45:20,277 --> 00:45:21,614
That’s the only way...

489
00:45:21,649 --> 00:45:27,043
we will produce jobs,
real jobs, jobs that sustain.

490
00:45:29,267 --> 00:45:33,698
The Trade Union Movement was
founded to protect workers.

491
00:45:33,733 --> 00:45:38,591
Now it persecutes them.
It stops them from working.

492
00:45:38,626 --> 00:45:42,416
It is killing jobs and it is bringing
this country to its knees.

493
00:45:42,451 --> 00:45:43,614
I say enough.

494
00:45:43,649 --> 00:45:48,275
It’s time to get up.
It’s time to go to work.

495
00:45:48,310 --> 00:45:53,491
It’s time to put the Great
back into Great Britain!

496
00:45:54,023 --> 00:46:06,932
xxx

497
00:46:07,033 --> 00:46:08,222
Give ‘em hell!

498
00:46:08,257 --> 00:46:12,280
You look magnificent.
Next stop Prime Minister.

499
00:46:12,315 --> 00:46:13,462
Let go.

500
00:46:13,497 --> 00:46:16,978
The leader of the Conservative
Party, Margaret Thatcher!

501
00:46:44,180 --> 00:46:48,468
Good night Margaret.
My money’s on the filly to win!

502
00:46:48,503 --> 00:46:51,647
Oh, thanks Airey. Goodnight.

503
00:47:01,883 --> 00:47:06,390
No. No, no! Airey!

504
00:47:13,776 --> 00:47:17,225
The Irish National Liberation Army
has claimed responsibility for the...

505
00:47:17,260 --> 00:47:22,074
death of Airey Neave, Margaret
Thatcher’s spokesman on Northern Ireland.

506
00:47:33,900 --> 00:47:37,151
<i>If you want to change the party,
lead it.</i>

507
00:47:37,186 --> 00:47:39,990
<i>If you want to change
the country, lead it.</i>

508
00:47:40,025 --> 00:47:43,186
<i>You’ve got it in you to
go the whole distance!</i>

509
00:47:46,648 --> 00:47:52,581
Now, as the test draws near,
I ask your help.

510
00:47:52,616 --> 00:47:57,535
That together we can shake off
the shackles of socialism

511
00:47:57,570 --> 00:48:02,219
and restore to greatness
this country that we love.

512
00:48:02,254 --> 00:48:06,607
And the only way is for the
Conservative Party to win!

513
00:48:07,793 --> 00:48:11,137
xxx

514
00:48:35,005 --> 00:48:37,792
It’s Friday the 4th of May,
an historic day for Britain,

515
00:48:37,827 --> 00:48:41,618
a Conservative government led by
Mrs. Thatcher is set to lead -

516
00:48:42,227 --> 00:48:47,863
Mrs Ghandi in India, but never in the West
has there been a woman Prime Minister.

517
00:48:47,898 --> 00:48:50,197
The place that she has secured
in British history, as...

518
00:48:50,232 --> 00:48:52,885
the first woman ever to be invited
to form a government.

519
00:48:52,920 --> 00:48:55,258
The bonus of one of the most
famous addresses in the world,

520
00:48:55,293 --> 00:48:56,778
Number 10 Downing Street.

521
00:48:56,813 --> 00:48:59,855
This is it, steady the buffs old girl.

522
00:49:08,660 --> 00:49:10,779
Good afternoon, Prime Minister.

523
00:49:12,081 --> 00:49:14,294
I should just like to say...

524
00:49:14,329 --> 00:49:17,835
that I take very seriously
the trust...

525
00:49:17,871 --> 00:49:20,405
the British people placed
in me today...

526
00:49:20,439 --> 00:49:26,117
and I will work hard every day to
live up to that responsibility.

527
00:49:26,152 --> 00:49:30,499
And now, I should like to share
with you a prayer...

528
00:49:30,534 --> 00:49:33,188
of St Francis of Assisi:

529
00:49:35,128 --> 00:49:39,721
''Where there is discord may
we bring harmony...

530
00:49:39,756 --> 00:49:44,533
Where there is error may we bring truth...

531
00:49:44,568 --> 00:49:48,815
Where there is doubt
may we bring faith...

532
00:49:48,850 --> 00:49:53,724
Where there is despair
may we bring hope''

533
00:50:05,201 --> 00:50:06,975
Shoulders back, tummies in!

534
00:50:09,252 --> 00:50:10,722
Oh. Thank you, Michael.

535
00:50:14,512 --> 00:50:16,096
Two, one.

536
00:50:34,820 --> 00:50:40,343
I’m perfectly healthy. There’s no
need for any of this.

537
00:50:40,378 --> 00:50:43,330
Just let them look under
the bonnet, MT.

538
00:50:44,031 --> 00:50:46,151
Check everything is hunky dory.

539
00:50:46,251 --> 00:50:50,897
Really it’s becoming quite tiresome.

540
00:50:50,932 --> 00:50:52,083
What is?
- You.

541
00:50:53,248 --> 00:50:56,774
I was on my own for
twenty four years...

542
00:50:56,809 --> 00:51:02,370
before I met you and I can manage
perfectly well without you now.

543
00:51:03,569 --> 00:51:08,565
So will you please go away
and stop bothering me.

544
00:51:08,600 --> 00:51:12,130
Just look straight at me,
straight ahead, that’s it.

545
00:51:13,374 --> 00:51:15,541
Are you noticing night sweats?
- No.

546
00:51:16,660 --> 00:51:18,210
Hallucinations?

547
00:51:19,336 --> 00:51:20,128
No.

548
00:51:22,180 --> 00:51:23,243
Sleep?

549
00:51:23,278 --> 00:51:27,512
Yes, I sleep.
Four, five hours a night.

550
00:51:27,548 --> 00:51:29,481
So you wake early?

551
00:51:30,072 --> 00:51:33,062
And I stay up late.
I always have.

552
00:51:34,073 --> 00:51:35,856
We just want to keep abreast
of it thats all.

553
00:51:35,892 --> 00:51:37,227
Yes. Of course.

554
00:51:38,761 --> 00:51:40,791
Grief is a very natural state.

555
00:51:41,786 --> 00:51:45,947
My husband has been gone
for years. Cancer.

556
00:51:46,520 --> 00:51:50,426
Carol says you’ve decided to let
his things go. Probably a good thing.

557
00:51:50,461 --> 00:51:53,419
Yes. It was my idea.
To Oxfam.

558
00:51:53,454 --> 00:51:57,688
Perfectly good stuff. People can
use these things.

559
00:51:59,747 --> 00:52:04,673
Still it must be a bit disorientating.
You are bound to be feeling.

560
00:52:04,707 --> 00:52:05,631
What?

561
00:52:06,827 --> 00:52:09,958
What am I
‘bound to be feeling’?

562
00:52:12,575 --> 00:52:14,553
People don’t ‘think’ any more.

563
00:52:14,588 --> 00:52:17,128
They ‘feel’.
‘How are you feeling?’

564
00:52:17,163 --> 00:52:19,676
‘Oh I don’t feel comfortable
with that’

565
00:52:19,711 --> 00:52:22,393
‘Oh, I’m so sorry but we,
the group were feeling...’

566
00:52:23,164 --> 00:52:26,421
D’you know, one of the
great problems of our age...

567
00:52:26,456 --> 00:52:28,976
is that we are governed
by people who care...

568
00:52:29,011 --> 00:52:33,658
more about feelings
than thoughts and ideas.

569
00:52:33,692 --> 00:52:38,153
Now thoughts and ideas.
That interests me.

570
00:52:38,188 --> 00:52:40,345
Ask me what I am thinking-

571
00:52:41,520 --> 00:52:43,395
What are you thinking, Margaret?

572
00:52:45,186 --> 00:52:47,652
Watch your thoughts,
for they become words.

573
00:52:47,687 --> 00:52:50,802
Watch your words,
for they become actions.

574
00:52:52,645 --> 00:52:56,417
Watch your actions,
for they become habits.

575
00:52:56,452 --> 00:53:00,679
Watch your habits, for
they become your character.

576
00:53:00,714 --> 00:53:04,733
And watch your character,
for it becomes your destiny.

577
00:53:04,768 --> 00:53:06,714
What we think, we become.

578
00:53:08,474 --> 00:53:10,278
My father always said that.

579
00:53:11,438 --> 00:53:14,201
And I think I am fine.

580
00:53:19,440 --> 00:53:23,187
But I do so appreciate
your kind concern.

581
00:53:29,972 --> 00:53:31,657
Oh, do please answer that.

582
00:53:31,692 --> 00:53:33,913
It might be someone who needs you.

583
00:53:37,473 --> 00:53:39,234
I’ll give Carol a quick
ring, let her...

584
00:53:39,269 --> 00:53:42,381
know we’re back, then I’ll put
your electric blanket on.

585
00:53:44,312 --> 00:53:46,647
Steady, steady, steady!

586
00:53:48,785 --> 00:53:51,258
Damn.
Fore!

587
00:53:52,628 --> 00:53:55,085
What about that medicine man, eh?

588
00:53:55,793 --> 00:53:58,456
Ah. Cold supper.

589
00:53:58,491 --> 00:54:00,938
Standards are slipping Margaret.

590
00:54:02,138 --> 00:54:04,898
Well you really gave it to that
quack didn’t you, darling?

591
00:54:04,933 --> 00:54:08,813
Just like the old days!
Hallucinations my eye!

592
00:54:08,848 --> 00:54:10,285
How dare he?

593
00:54:10,320 --> 00:54:12,455
But then you give us all the run
around, don’t you?

594
00:54:13,798 --> 00:54:18,366
I know you can hear me, sweetheart,
so there’s no use pretending you can’t.

595
00:54:20,004 --> 00:54:22,505
Enough. Denis, enough!

596
00:54:23,167 --> 00:54:24,379
Dismissed!

597
00:54:32,343 --> 00:54:34,666
She does it in the end.
Kills him-

598
00:54:37,168 --> 00:54:39,621
I don’t know why you’re
being so scratchy.

599
00:54:39,656 --> 00:54:42,251
It’s not as if you’ve got anyone
else to talk to.

600
00:54:42,286 --> 00:54:46,040
When the Himalayan peasant meets
the he-bear in his pride -

601
00:54:46,075 --> 00:54:49,798
You know, it’s a marvel to me that you
can still quote huge chunks of Kipling...

602
00:54:49,833 --> 00:54:52,379
but try remembering the name
of that woman who’s...

603
00:54:52,414 --> 00:54:54,853
just made you that
godawful cold collation.

604
00:54:54,886 --> 00:54:56,399
No?

605
00:54:56,434 --> 00:54:58,285
Come on.
You can do it.

606
00:54:58,320 --> 00:54:59,629
Month of the year.

607
00:55:00,250 --> 00:55:03,836
One syllable.
Rhymes with moon.

608
00:55:04,436 --> 00:55:06,799
June.
- June! Bingo.

609
00:55:06,834 --> 00:55:08,334
Knew you’d get
there in the end.

610
00:55:09,412 --> 00:55:14,199
“When the Himalayan peasant
meets the he-bear in his pride...

611
00:55:14,234 --> 00:55:18,092
He shouts to scare the monster,
who will often turn aside...

612
00:55:18,127 --> 00:55:22,855
